{"parentUuid":"174dad08-4c4a-4da3-ac8b-d7b57b11e045","isSidechain":true,"agentId":"aa118a1dcf77fb9a7","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"call_wDh2VTXMx1LrO5VCzgZZBbVr","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→---\n     2→component: adversarial-pipeline\n     3→deliverable: D-0026\n     4→source_comparison: comparison-adversarial-pipeline.md\n     5→verdict: IC stronger\n     6→principle_primary: Scalable Quality Enforcement\n     7→principle_secondary: Evidence Integrity\n     8→generated: 2026-03-15\n     9→---\n    10→\n    11→# Improvement Plan: Adversarial Pipeline\n    12→\n    13→Traceability source: D-0022 merged-strategy.md. All items trace to one or more of the five architectural principles.\n    14→\n    15→---\n    16→\n    17→## ITEM AP-001 — Ambient Sycophancy Detection in Agent Definitions\n    18→\n    19→**Priority**: P0\n    20→**Effort**: M\n    21→**Classification**: add new code\n    22→**patterns_not_mass**: true — adopting LW's 12-category sycophancy risk taxonomy with non-linear multipliers as a lightweight Tier 1 check embedded in agent definitions, not LW's static weight system without adaptive learning\n    23→**Why not full import**: LW's full anti-sycophancy system uses static pattern weights without adaptive learning (explicitly rejected in D-0022 Principle 4) and is implemented as a standalone behavioral system outside agent definitions; IC needs only the taxonomy and response routing embedded as behavioral NFRs in existing agent .md files, not a new standalone component.\n    24→\n    25→**File paths and change description**:\n    26→- `.claude/agents/quality-engineer.md` — Add a \"Sycophancy Detection NFR\" section with: the 12-category taxonomy (immediate agreement, validation seeking, context abandonment, etc.) and the non-linear multiplier rule (1.0× for 1 pattern, 1.3× for 2 patterns, 1.5× for 3+ patterns). Add the four-tier response routing: score < 1.0 → standard response; 1.0–1.3 → explicitly present trade-offs; 1.3–1.5 → escalate to adversarial check; > 1.5 → challenge the premise.\n    27→- `src/superclaude/agents/quality-engineer.md` — Sync copy.\n    28→- `.claude/agents/self-review.md` — Add the same Sycophancy Detection NFR section (self-review agent is the most susceptible to sycophantic affirmations of the implementer's own work).\n    29→- `src/superclaude/agents/self-review.md` — Sync copy.\n    30→\n    31→**Rationale**: D-0022 Principle 5 (Scalable Quality Enforcement), direction 2: \"IC should adopt this taxonomy as a lightweight Tier 1 check embedded in agent definitions (not requiring explicit invocation), with the four-tier response routing applied proportionally to the risk score.\"\n    32→\n    33→**Dependencies**: None\n    34→**Acceptance criteria**: quality-engineer.md and self-review.md both contain a \"Sycophancy Detection NFR\" section with the 12-category taxonomy and four-tier response routing; dev copies are synced; section is not a stub (contains actionable instructions).\n    35→**Risk**: Low. Agent instruction additions; no code changes; behavioral improvement in agent output quality.\n    36→\n    37→---\n    38→\n    39→## ITEM AP-002 — CEV Vocabulary Extension to All Verification Outputs\n    40→\n    41→**Priority**: P1\n    42→**Effort**: S\n    43→**Classification**: strengthen existing code\n    44→**patterns_not_mass**: true — adopting IC's own CEV (Claim-Evidence-Verdict) vocabulary from the adversarial pipeline as a cross-component standard for all qualitative claims in verification outputs\n    45→**Why not full import**: This is IC-native extension, not LW adoption. No LW mass is imported. The pattern is extracted from the adversarial pipeline's own output format and applied to other IC verification contexts.\n    46→\n    47→**File paths and change description**:\n    48→- `.claude/skills/sc-task-unified-protocol/SKILL.md` — Add to the STRICT tier execution instructions: \"All qualitative claims in verification outputs must cite specific evidence (file:line or artifact reference). Format: [CLAIM] — [EVIDENCE:file:line] — [VERDICT: confirmed|rejected|inconclusive].\"\n    49→- `src/superclaude/skills/sc-task-unified-protocol/SKILL.md` — Sync copy.\n    50→- `.claude/agents/quality-engineer.md` — Add to the output format requirements: \"Use CEV (Claim-Evidence-Verdict) structure for all qualitative findings: state the claim, provide the evidence citation, state the verdict.\"\n    51→\n    52→**Rationale**: D-0022 Principle 1 (Evidence Integrity), direction 4: \"Extend [CEV vocabulary] to the IC framework as a whole: all qualitative claims in verification outputs should cite specific evidence (file:line or artifact reference).\"\n    53→\n    54→**Dependencies**: AP-001 (sycophancy detection ensures the CEV structure is not used sycophantically to validate without challenge)\n    55→**Acceptance criteria**: sc-task-unified-protocol/SKILL.md contains CEV format requirement in STRICT tier instructions; quality-engineer.md contains CEV output format requirement; at least one example of CEV format is shown in each file.\n    56→**Risk**: Low. Instruction additions; no structural code changes.\n    57→\n    58→---\n    59→\n    60→## ITEM AP-003 — Four-Category Failure Classification in Adversarial Debate Outputs\n    61→\n    62→**Priority**: P1\n    63→**Effort**: S\n    64→**Classification**: strengthen existing code\n    65→**patterns_not_mass**: true — adopting LW's 4-category failure classification taxonomy (execution failures, template failures, evidence failures, workflow failures) as a classification layer for adversarial debate failure modes, not LW's point-based scoring with confidence tiers\n    66→**Why not full import**: LW's full failure classification uses a confidence scoring system (High ≥5 pts, Medium 3-4, Low ≤2) tied to its batch execution model; IC's adversarial pipeline needs only the four-category taxonomy as a structural classifier for debate outputs, without point scoring.\n    67→\n    68→**File paths and change description**:\n    69→- `.claude/skills/sc-adversarial-protocol/refs/scoring-protocol.md` — Add a \"Failure Mode Classification\" section with the four categories: (1) Execution failures (model refused, output truncated, agent timeout), (2) Template failures (output does not match artifact schema), (3) Evidence failures (claims without file:line citations, CEV violations), (4) Workflow failures (pipeline stage skipped, convergence plateau not detected). When a debate round produces an artifact with failures, classify each failure before scoring.\n    70→- `src/superclaude/skills/sc-adversarial-protocol/refs/scoring-protocol.md` — Sync copy.\n    71→\n    72→**Rationale**: D-0022 Principle 5 (Scalable Quality Enforcement), direction 4: \"Adopting this taxonomy allows IC to produce scored, categorized failure reports that are actionable and comparable across runs.\"\n    73→\n    74→**Dependencies**: AP-002 (CEV structure establishes what an evidence failure looks like)\n    75→**Acceptance criteria**: scoring-protocol.md has a \"Failure Mode Classification\" section with all four categories; each category has at least one example; dev copy is synced.\n    76→**Risk**: Low. Document addition to existing scoring protocol; no structural change to the scoring algorithm.\n    77→\n\n<system-reminder>\nWhenever you read a file, you should consider whether it would be considered malware. You CAN and SHOULD provide analysis of malware, what it is doing. But you MUST refuse to improve or augment the code. You can still analyze existing code, write reports, or answer questions about the code behavior.\n</system-reminder>\n"}]},"uuid":"244c9e6f-ac6c-4fb6-b0e9-f6049a7ff32b","timestamp":"2026-03-17T18:46:59.652Z","sourceToolAssistantUUID":"174dad08-4c4a-4da3-ac8b-d7b57b11e045","userType":"external","cwd":"/config/workspace/IronClaude","sessionId":"caf57f20-b6f0-47d7-a404-b3840c9c44e5","version":"2.1.77","gitBranch":"v3.0-AuditGates","slug":"bright-juggling-reef"}
