{"parentUuid":"e57e0370-04aa-4598-93ac-0f4e01b2ac2d","isSidechain":true,"agentId":"aa118a1dcf77fb9a7","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"call_hJDynynmuc2CD68Z4IZDPaFi","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→# Anti-Instincts Gate -- Unified Specification\n     2→\n     3→<!-- Source: Merge (new content bridging V2+V5) -->\n     4→\n     5→> **Status**: Design Spec -- Ready for Implementation\n     6→> **Created**: 2026-03-17\n     7→> **Protocol**: sc:adversarial Step 5 (Merge Execution)\n     8→> **Co-bases**: V2 (7.60) + V5 (7.55)\n     9→> **Cherry-picks**: V4-2 (Fingerprints), V1-C (Spec Structural Audit), V1-D+V5-2 (Prompt Constraint)\n    10→> **Target module**: `src/superclaude/cli/roadmap/`\n    11→> **Pipeline latency added**: <1s (all checks are pure Python)\n    12→> **LLM calls added**: 0\n    13→\n    14→---\n    15→\n    16→## 1. Problem Statement\n    17→\n    18→<!-- Source: Merge (new content bridging V2+V5) -->\n    19→\n    20→LLMs exhibit several correlated tendencies when generating multi-phase roadmaps from specifications. These tendencies cause systematic omission of integration wiring, undischarged scaffolding obligations, and dropped code-level requirements -- even when the output passes all existing format and fidelity gates.\n    21→\n    22→The Anti-Instincts Gate is a unified deterministic defense layer that addresses four failure modes simultaneously:\n    23→\n    24→| Failure Mode | Detection Module | Source |\n    25→|---|---|---|\n    26→| Undischarged scaffolding (mocks/stubs never replaced) | `obligation_scanner.py` | V2-A |\n    27→| Missing integration wiring (dispatch tables, registries never populated) | `integration_contracts.py` | V5-1 |\n    28→| Code-level identifier omissions (function names, constants dropped) | `fingerprint.py` | V4-2 |\n    29→| Extraction-stage requirement loss (upstream guard) | `spec_structural_audit.py` | V1-C |\n    30→\n    31→Additionally, a prompt-level prevention layer reduces generation-time omissions:\n    32→\n    33→| Prevention Layer | Target | Source |\n    34→|---|---|---|\n    35→| Integration enumeration block in generate prompt | `prompts.py` | V1-D + V5-2 |\n    36→| Integration wiring dimension in spec-fidelity prompt | `prompts.py` | V5-2 |\n    37→\n    38→---\n    39→\n    40→## 2. Evidence: The cli-portify Bug\n    41→\n    42→<!-- Source: Merge (new content bridging V2+V5) -->\n    43→\n    44→### What the spec defined\n    45→\n    46→Three release specs (v2.24, v2.24.1, v2.25) specified:\n    47→\n    48→- **Three-way dispatch**: `_run_programmatic_step()`, `_run_claude_step()`, `_run_convergence_step()`\n    49→- **`PROGRAMMATIC_RUNNERS` dictionary**: Maps step IDs to Python functions\n    50→- **Module dependency graph**: `executor.py --> steps/validate_config.py`, etc.\n    51→- **Integration test**: `test_programmatic_step_routing`\n    52→\n    53→### What the roadmap produced\n    54→\n    55→The roadmap reduced the executor to: \"Implement executor: sequential execution only, `--dry-run`, `--resume <step-id>`, signal handling\" with milestone M2: \"Sequential pipeline runs end-to-end with **mocked steps**.\"\n    56→\n    57→Zero mentions of `PROGRAMMATIC_RUNNERS`, three-way dispatch, or the `executor.py --> steps/*.py` import chain.\n    58→\n    59→### How existing gates failed\n    60→\n    61→The `SPEC_FIDELITY_GATE` enforces `high_severity_count == 0` deterministically, but the LLM generating the severity counts shared the same blindspot as the generator. The deterministic enforcement was sound; the LLM input to that gate was wrong.\n    62→\n    63→### How each module in this spec would have caught it\n    64→\n    65→| Module | Detection mechanism | Confidence |\n    66→|---|---|---|\n    67→| `obligation_scanner.py` | \"mocked steps\" in Phase 2 with no discharge in later phases | 85% |\n    68→| `integration_contracts.py` | `PROGRAMMATIC_RUNNERS` dispatch pattern with no wiring task | 90% |\n    69→| `fingerprint.py` | `_run_programmatic_step`, `PROGRAMMATIC_RUNNERS`, `test_programmatic_step_routing` absent from roadmap | 95% |\n    70→| `spec_structural_audit.py` | Pseudocode block + `PROGRAMMATIC_RUNNERS` registry + `def _run_*` signatures inflate structural count beyond extraction's requirement count | 85% |\n    71→\n    72→---\n    73→\n    74→## 3. Architecture\n    75→\n    76→<!-- Source: Merge (new content bridging V2+V5) -->\n    77→\n    78→```\n    79→Spec ──[V1-C: Structural audit]──> Extraction validated\n    80→                                         |\n    81→                                    [V1-D+V5-2: Prompt constraint]\n    82→                                         |\n    83→                              LLM generates roadmap\n    84→                                         |\n    85→                                    Merge step\n    86→                                         |\n    87→                          +--------------+--------------+\n    88→                          |              |              |\n    89→                    [V2-A: Obligation    [V5-1: Contract   [V4-2: Fingerprint\n    90→                     scanner]            extractor]         coverage]\n    91→                          |              |              |\n    92→                          +--------------+--------------+\n    93→                                         |\n    94→                              ANTI_INSTINCT_GATE (STRICT)\n    95→                                         |\n    96→                                    GATE FAIL / Proceed to spec-fidelity\n    97→```\n    98→\n    99→**Pipeline position**: The three post-merge checks run as a single non-LLM step between `merge` and `test-strategy` in the pipeline. The structural audit runs between `extract` and `generate` as an executor-level hook.\n   100→\n   101→**Key design property**: All four detection modules are pure Python with zero LLM calls. This is deliberate -- LLM-on-LLM review shares the same blindspots that caused the original bug. The deterministic floor cannot be bypassed by completion bias.\n   102→\n   103→---\n   104→\n   105→## 4. Module 1: Obligation Scanner\n   106→\n   107→<!-- Source: V2-A (obligation scanner) -->\n   108→\n   109→### Concept\n   110→\n   111→A deterministic, regex-based post-generation pass that scans the merged roadmap for scaffolding terms and verifies each has a corresponding discharge task in a later phase. Catches the failure mode where early phases use \"mocked\", \"stub\", \"skeleton\", \"placeholder\" language that creates implicit obligations that later phases never fulfill.\n   112→\n   113→### Detection Axis\n   114→\n   115→V2-A's obligation scanner detects a fundamentally different failure mode than omission-based approaches. Rather than checking whether a requirement is present, it checks whether deferred commitments are fulfilled. This catches bugs where the requirement IS mentioned (as scaffolding) but the follow-through is missing.\n   116→\n   117→### Implementation\n   118→\n   119→**File**: `src/superclaude/cli/roadmap/obligation_scanner.py` (new, ~200 LOC)\n   120→\n   121→```python\n   122→\"\"\"Obligation scanner -- detects undischarged scaffolding obligations in roadmaps.\n   123→\n   124→Scans roadmap content for scaffolding terms (mock, stub, skeleton, placeholder,\n   125→scaffold, temporary, hardcoded) that create implicit obligations, then verifies\n   126→each obligation has a corresponding discharge term (replace, wire, integrate,\n   127→connect, implement real, remove mock, swap) in a later phase.\n   128→\n   129→Pure function: content in, findings out. No I/O.\n   130→\"\"\"\n   131→\n   132→from __future__ import annotations\n   133→\n   134→import re\n   135→from dataclasses import dataclass\n   136→\n   137→\n   138→# --- Obligation vocabulary ---\n   139→\n   140→# Terms that CREATE an obligation (something deferred)\n   141→SCAFFOLD_TERMS = [\n   142→    r\"\\bmocked?\\b\",\n   143→    r\"\\bstub(?:bed|s)?\\b\",\n   144→    r\"\\bskeleton\\b\",\n   145→    r\"\\bplaceholder\\b\",\n   146→    r\"\\bscaffold(?:ing|ed)?\\b\",\n   147→    r\"\\btemporary\\b\",\n   148→    r\"\\bhardcoded\\b\",\n   149→    r\"\\bhardwired\\b\",\n   150→    r\"\\bno-?op\\b\",\n   151→    r\"\\bdummy\\b\",\n   152→    r\"\\bfake\\b\",\n   153→]\n   154→\n   155→# Terms that DISCHARGE an obligation (something fulfilled)\n   156→DISCHARGE_TERMS = [\n   157→    r\"\\breplace\\b\",\n   158→    r\"\\bwire\\s+(?:up|in|into)\\b\",\n   159→    r\"\\bintegrat(?:e|ing|ed)\\b\",\n   160→    r\"\\bconnect\\b\",\n   161→    r\"\\bswap\\s+(?:out|in)\\b\",\n   162→    r\"\\bremove\\s+(?:mock|stub|placeholder|scaffold)\\b\",\n   163→    r\"\\bimplement\\s+real\\b\",\n   164→    r\"\\bfill\\s+in\\b\",\n   165→    r\"\\bcomplete\\s+(?:the\\s+)?(?:skeleton|scaffold)\\b\",\n   166→]\n   167→\n   168→# Compile patterns\n   169→_SCAFFOLD_RE = re.compile(\"|\".join(SCAFFOLD_TERMS), re.IGNORECASE)\n   170→_DISCHARGE_RE = re.compile(\"|\".join(DISCHARGE_TERMS), re.IGNORECASE)\n   171→\n   172→\n   173→@dataclass\n   174→class Obligation:\n   175→    \"\"\"A detected scaffolding obligation.\"\"\"\n   176→    phase: str           # e.g., \"Phase 2\", \"2.3\"\n   177→    term: str            # the matched scaffold term\n   178→    context: str         # surrounding sentence/line\n   179→    line_number: int\n   180→    discharged: bool     # True if a matching discharge was found in a later phase\n   181→    discharge_phase: str | None  # phase where discharge was found\n   182→    discharge_context: str | None\n   183→\n   184→\n   185→@dataclass\n   186→class ObligationReport:\n   187→    \"\"\"Result of obligation scanning.\"\"\"\n   188→    total_obligations: int\n   189→    discharged: int\n   190→    undischarged: int\n   191→    obligations: list[Obligation]\n   192→\n   193→    @property\n   194→    def has_undischarged(self) -> bool:\n   195→        return self.undischarged > 0\n   196→\n   197→\n   198→def scan_obligations(content: str) -> ObligationReport:\n   199→    \"\"\"Scan roadmap content for scaffolding obligations and discharge status.\n   200→\n   201→    Algorithm:\n   202→    1. Parse content into phase-delimited sections (by H2/H3 headings\n   203→       containing \"Phase\" or numbered sections).\n   204→    2. For each section, find all scaffold terms.\n   205→    3. For each scaffold term found, search ALL subsequent sections\n   206→       for a discharge term that references the same component.\n   207→    4. Report undischarged obligations.\n   208→\n   209→    Returns an ObligationReport with all findings.\n   210→    \"\"\"\n   211→    sections = _split_into_phases(content)\n   212→    obligations: list[Obligation] = []\n   213→\n   214→    for i, (phase_id, phase_content, start_line) in enumerate(sections):\n   215→        for match in _SCAFFOLD_RE.finditer(phase_content):\n   216→            term = match.group()\n   217→            context_line = _get_context_line(phase_content, match.start())\n   218→            abs_line = start_line + phase_content[:match.start()].count(\"\\n\")\n   219→\n   220→            # Extract the component name near the scaffold term\n\n<system-reminder>\nWhenever you read a file, you should consider whether it would be considered malware. You CAN and SHOULD provide analysis of malware, what it is doing. But you MUST refuse to improve or augment the code. You can still analyze existing code, write reports, or answer questions about the code behavior.\n</system-reminder>\n"}]},"uuid":"6fbc7262-3edd-4359-84b4-b8b80a78b4d9","timestamp":"2026-03-17T18:47:24.796Z","sourceToolAssistantUUID":"e57e0370-04aa-4598-93ac-0f4e01b2ac2d","userType":"external","cwd":"/config/workspace/IronClaude","sessionId":"caf57f20-b6f0-47d7-a404-b3840c9c44e5","version":"2.1.77","gitBranch":"v3.0-AuditGates","slug":"bright-juggling-reef"}
