3.1_unified-audit-gating-v1.2.1/unified-audit-gating-v1.2.1-release-spec.md` already pushes part of the same evidence-discipline goal: “Critical claims cite source file + section label” (Section 0.3), failed checks must include evidence refs of `file path` or `file:line` (Section 5.3), and `GateCheckEvent` carries `evidence_refs[]` (Section 6.3). This overlaps with AP-002’s requirement that verification claims cite evidence, but it does not establish AP-002’s full CEV triad or extend it to all verification outputs via `sc-task-unified-protocol` and `quality-engineer.md`.  \n  - `/config/workspace/IronClaude/.dev/releases/backlog/v3.0_fidelity-refactor_/wiring-verification-gate-v1.0-release-spec.md` also partially overlaps on structured evidence output: report findings must include file and line references, and the emitted report uses a strict evidence-bearing format (Sections 4.3, 6.3, 10).  \n  - `/config/workspace/IronClaude/.dev/releases/backlog/v3.05_Anti-instincts_/anti-instincts-gate-unified.md` strengthens deterministic roadmap validation, but it does not define a CEV output contract across verification surfaces.  \n- Recommendation: REVISE — narrow this item so it explicitly fills the gap left by the refactors: standardize **CEV as a cross-skill/output presentation format** in `sc-task-unified-protocol` and `quality-engineer.md`, while reusing the refactors’ existing evidence-citation requirements instead of re-proposing generic “claims need evidence.”\n\n**ITEM AP-003** — Four-Category Failure Classification in Adversarial Debate Outputs  \n- Status: OVERLAPPING  \n- Evidence:  \n  - `/config/workspace/IronClaude/.dev/releases/backlog/v3.1_unified-audit-gating-v1.2.1/unified-audit-gating-v1.2.1-release-spec.md` introduces a normalized failure taxonomy for audit gating: `policy | transient | system | timeout | unknown` (Sections 3.1, 5.1). That partially overlaps with AP-003’s desire to classify failures systematically, but it is a different taxonomy, aimed at gate execution/state handling rather than adversarial debate artifact analysis.  \n  - The same spec ties failure classification into deterministic contracts and events via `failure_class` on `GateResult` and structured causes on transition/check events (Sections 6.1, 6.3), which covers part of the “categorized, actionable reports” goal but not AP-003’s proposed `execution/template/evidence/workflow` breakdown in `sc-adversarial-protocol/refs/scoring-protocol.md`.  \n  - `/config/workspace/IronClaude/.dev/releases/backlog/v3.0_fidelity-refactor_/wiring-verification-gate-v1.0-release-spec.md` classifies findings by `finding_type` (`unwired_callable`, `orphan_module`, `unwired_registry`) and severity, but not adversarial debate failure modes (Sections 4.1, 4.4).  \n  - `/config/workspace/IronClaude/.dev/releases/backlog/v3.05_Anti-instincts_/anti-instincts-gate-unified.md` defines deterministic checks and contradiction resolutions, but no adversarial debate failure-mode layer.  \n- Recommendation: REVISE — keep the adversarial-specific classifier, but align it with the newer v1.2.1 failure-class model instead of introducing an entirely separate vocabulary. For example, position `execution/template/evidence/workflow` as an adversarial sub-classification layered under the broader gate failure framework.\n\nOverall disposition: `/config/workspace/IronClaude/.dev/releases/backlog/v3.5RigorFlowMerger/improve-adversarial-pipeline.md` remains mostly valid after the three refactors, but it is no longer clean-room greenfield work. AP-001 stands independently, while AP-002 and AP-003 now partially overlap with the new evidence and failure-contract machinery introduced mainly by `/config/workspace/IronClaude/.dev/releases/backlog/v3.1_unified-audit-gating-v1.2.1/unified-audit-gating-v1.2.1-release-spec.md`. The file should be retained, but AP-002 and AP-003 should be reframed as targeted extensions on top of the refactors rather than parallel standards."}],"stop_reason":null}